2.1 Word-of-mouth communication Much of the work done on word-of-mouth communication in the context of social psychology and marketing research has focused on its forms and determinants , suggesting that word-of-mouth arises in three possible ways : it may be induced by a particular transaction or product experience [ 11 ] , particularly when that transaction has been an especially good or bad one [ 1 ] ; it may be solicited from others [ 10 ] , usually when the task involved is difficult , ambiguous , or new [ 7 ] ; and it may come about when 